4.2 Conditional Statements
A conditional statement determines what code is evaluated. In general, conditional statements look something like this:
if (condition){
  stuff to do
}
  else{
  other stuff to do
}
When the computer encounters a conditional statement, it first checks to see if the condition is met (TRUE) or if is is not met (FALSE). If the condition is TRUE, then the computer will execute the “stuff to do” inside the first set of {}. If the condition is FALSE, then the computer will execute the “other stuff to do” inside the second set of {}

4.2.1 Conditional Statements in R
In R, conditional statements look something like this:

x &lt;- 3

if (x &gt; 2) { 
  y &lt;- 8
  } else {
  y &lt;- 4
  }

There are a few things we need to notice about the syntax. First, we are using two words if and else to build the control flow. These are reserved names that R recognizes exactly for this type of task. Second, the condition being checked comes after if and is contained in parentheses (x &gt; 2). The “stuff to do” when the condition is TRUE is enclosed in {} immediately after the if() statement. If the condition is FALSE, then R will execute the “other stuff to do” contained in the {} after else.
What value should y have?






ImportantCode Style



We could have written the above code as:

if (x &gt; 2) y &lt;- 8  else y &lt;- 4

and we would have gotten the same result. So, why should we make our code so long?
A braced expression, {}, defines the most important hierarchy of R code. So, we want to make the hierarchy easy to understand. To do this, our code should follow these three principles:

A { should be the last character on the line (e.g., if (x &gt; 2) { ).
The contents inside the { should be indented by two spaces.
A } should be the first character on the line (e.g., } else {)
A space should be included between if and the ( starting the condition

Each of these principles of code style come from the Syntax section of the tidyverse style guide. We will use this style guide throughout the course!








Check-inCheck In




Which of the following is the correct way to format a conditional statement?





if (num &lt; 100){
  print(num)
}
else {
  print("banana")
}





if (num &lt; 100){
  print(num)
} else {
  print("banana")
}





if (num &lt; 100){ print(num) } else { print("banana") }





if (num &lt; 100) print(num) else print("banana") 




4.2.2 Conditional Statements as Diagrams
We find it quite useful to represent conditional statements as diagrams. By drawing out the diagram (even if it is simple), you can more clearly anticipate what the result of the process will be.


Diagram of a simple conditional (if/else) statement







Check-inCheck In




With if + else you have ____ condition(s) to check and ____ possible outcome(s).

4.3 Chaining Conditional Statements
In our previous conditional statement we only used if and else, but that only works if you have two possible outcomes or one condition you need to check. In many cases we have more than one condition to check, so we will need to modify our conditional statement.
When we have more than one condition to check, we can use an else if () statement. else if () works similar to an if () statement, where you specify a condition to check in the parentheses. This looks something like:
if (condition 1) {
  stuff to do 
} else if (condition 2) {
  other stuff to do
} else {
  other other stuff to do
}

4.3.1 Multiple Conditions for Tax Brackets
Suppose we wanted to create conditional statements to know how much in federal taxes someone in the US might pay. Based on the current IRS tax rates we have the following outcomes1:


Income Range
Taxes



$0 to $11,925
10%


$11,926 to $48,475
12%


$48,476 $103,350
22%


$103,351 $197,300
24%


$197,301 $250,525
32%


$250,526 $626,350
35%


$626,351 and above
37%



Step 1: Draw out the diagram for the conditional statements. What conditions are being checked at each stage? If a condition is true what is the outcome? If a condition is false, what happens?






TipCheck Your Answer









Step 2: Translate your diagram into R code!






TipCheck Your Answer






if (income &lt; 11925) {
  0.10
  } else if (income &lt;= 48475) {
    0.12
  } else if (income &lt;= 103350) {
    0.22
  } else if (income &lt;= 197300) {
    0.24
  } else if (income &lt;= 250525) {
    0.32
  } else if (income &lt; 626350){
    0.35
  } else {
    0.37
  }




Okay, let’s try it out! A “typical” Assistant Professor in the College of Science and Math at Cal Poly makes $95,000. Based on your diagram, how much would a professor pay in taxes?
Let’s check! Setting income to 95000, our conditional statements tell us that the professor will pay 0.22 or 22% in taxes.




income &lt;- 95000

if (income &lt; 11925) {
  0.10
  } else if (income &lt;= 48475) {
    0.12
  } else if (income &lt;= 103350) {
    0.22
  } else if (income &lt;= 197300) {
    0.24
  } else if (income &lt;= 250525) {
    0.32
  } else if (income &lt; 626350){
    0.35
  } else {
    0.37
    }

[1] 0.22








Check-inCheck In




In the IRS tax brackets we had ____ possible outcomes and ____ conditions that needed to be checked.
In general, if you have \(n\) possible outcomes, you will always have ____ conditions to check.



What if we tried salaries for a variety of CSU employees? Jeffrey Armstrong, Cal Poly’s President is paid $611,203 2, Midred Garcia, the CSU Chancellor is paid $795,000 3, and a full-time janitor at Cal Poly can expect to make somewhere around $45,000.
Let’s put these three salaries through our conditional statements to figure out how much each employee will pay in taxes.

income &lt;- c(611203, 795000, 45000)

if (income &lt; 11925) {
  tax &lt;- 0.10
  } else if (income &lt;= 48475) {
    0.12
  } else if (income &lt;= 103350) {
    0.22
  } else if (income &lt;= 197300) {
    0.24
  } else if (income &lt;= 250525) {
    0.32
  } else if (income &lt; 626350){
    0.35
  } else {
    0.37
  }

Error in `if (income &lt; 11925) ...`:
! the condition has length &gt; 1


Oh no! Our conditionals didn’t work. What happened?
The error message we got ("the condition has length &gt; 1") may seem strange at first, but it is actually incredibly informative.
What the error is telling us is that if (income &lt; 11925) could not be evaluated because income has a length that is greater than 1. If we examine income &lt; 11925, we notice that it returns a vector of three TRUE/FALSE results; one for each of the three incomes.

income &lt; 11925

[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE


Therefore, our code was equivalent to if(c(FALSE, FALSE, TRUE)). An if() statement needs a single “yes/no” to determine if the code inside gets run or not, so these statements can only work for scalar vectors (i.e., vectors with a single value)

5.3 Debugging
Sometimes function writing doesn’t go as smoothly as what we’ve walked you through. Sometimes your function outputs something unexpected or sometimes it doesn’t run at all. This can be very frustrating, but there are a few methods you can used to try and hunt down the problem.

5.3.1 print() Statements
Suppose our function wasn’t working as intended.

x &lt;- 10:20
rescale(x, method = "min-max")

 [1] -1.5075567 -1.2060454 -0.9045340 -0.6030227 -0.3015113  0.0000000
 [7]  0.3015113  0.6030227  0.9045340  1.2060454  1.5075567


How do we know it’s not working as intended? Well, with min-max scaling, the largest value should be 1 and there should be no negative numbers.
One method for debugging is to add a print() statement into the body of the function. A print() statement does exactly what it sounds like, it prints the value of an object. For example, print(nums) would output 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20, NA, 35, 36, 37, 38, 39, 40, NA. Let’s see how this might look.
Here is the code for the broken function:

rescale &lt;- function(x, na.rm = FALSE, method){

  if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - min(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(x, na.rm = TRUE) - min(x, na.rm = TRUE))
  } else if (method == "minmax" & na.rm == FALSE) {
    (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))
  } else if (method == "normalize" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  } else{
    (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
  }
}

You might have already spotted our error, but let’s suppose it was less obvious. Since it seems like the incorrect method is being used, we could add a print() statement at the beginning of the function to print out the value of method being input into the control flow.

rescale &lt;- function(x, na.rm = FALSE, method){

  print(method)

  if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - min(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(x, na.rm = TRUE) - min(x, na.rm = TRUE))
  } else if (method == "minmax" & na.rm == FALSE) {
    (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))
  } else if (method == "normalize" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  } else{
    (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
  }
}


rescale(x, method = "min-max")

[1] "min-max"


 [1] -1.5075567 -1.2060454 -0.9045340 -0.6030227 -0.3015113  0.0000000
 [7]  0.3015113  0.6030227  0.9045340  1.2060454  1.5075567


Okay, so the value of method is what we expect ("min-max"), but the output is still wrong. By knowing the value of method we can go back and check where this value is being used. Doing this, we should notice that in the first else if () we’ve used "minmax" instead of "min-max". So, rescale(x, method = "min-max") was being thrown into the last condition (else) because na.rm was FALSE and the method didn’t match any of the values included in the control flow!

5.3.2 Running the Function Body
Another method for finding the bug in a function is to run the function body line by line. To do this, you first need to create objects that correspond to the function’s arguments. The rescale() function has three arguments (x, na.rm, and method), so we will need to create three objects with values that should be used.

x &lt;- 10:20
method &lt;- "min-max"
na.rm &lt;- FALSE

Now that we have objects for each of the function arguments, we can run the inside of the function. Specifically, we run this code:

  if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - min(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(x, na.rm = TRUE) - min(x, na.rm = TRUE))
  } else if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == FALSE) {
    (x - min(values)) / (max(values) - min(values))
  } else if (method == "normalize" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  } else{
    (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
  }

Error:
! object 'values' not found


By running the body of the function we can see that the code is using an object named values somewhere. The culprit is again the first else if () line where min(values) is used instead of min(x).

5.4 Input validation
When we write functions we know what type of inputs the function should use. However, someone else using our function might not know what the function expects. We will walk you through a series of input checks from simple to more complex,

5.4.1 Checking a Single Data Type
It might be obvious to us that the rescale() function should only be used with numeric values, but that might not be clear to someone else. We can prevent someone from giving our function a non-numeric input by adding a simple check at the beginning of the function:

rescale &lt;- function(x, na.rm = FALSE, method){

  # check if x is a numeric vector
  stopifnot(is.numeric(x))

  if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - min(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(x, na.rm = TRUE) - min(x, na.rm = TRUE))
  } else if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == FALSE) {
    (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))
  } else if (method == "normalize" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  } else{
    (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
  }
}

The stopifnot() function takes one input, the condition you want to check. Here, we are checking if x is a numeric vector. The is.numeric() function will output two possible values, TRUE and FLASE. If the output is FALSE, then stopifnot() will terminate the function.

letters &lt;- c("a", "b", "c", "d")
rescale(letters, method = "min-max")

Error in `rescale()`:
! is.numeric(x) is not TRUE








5.4.2 Checking Multiple Data Types
In a similar vein, we could check multiple data types still using the stopifnot() function. We also know the na.rm argument should be a logical value, and the method argument should be a character value. Let’s add these checks into the function!

rescale &lt;- function(x, na.rm = FALSE, method){

  # check if all inputs are correct data type
  stopifnot(is.numeric(x), 
            is.logical(na.rm), 
            is.character(method)
            )

  if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - min(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(x, na.rm = TRUE) - min(x, na.rm = TRUE))
  } else if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == FALSE) {
    (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))
  } else if (method == "normalize" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  } else{
    (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
  }
}

You might wonder why we don’t have three stopifnot()s, one for each condition:

stopifnot(is.numeric(x)) 
stopifnot(is.logical(na.rm))
stopifnot(is.character(method))

That is a great question! When you give stopifnot() multiple inputs (e.g., stopifnot(is.numeric(x), is.logical(na.rm)), every input must be TRUE simultaneously for the function to run. If any of the inputs are FALSE the function will stop.
This is the same as joining these statements with an &:

stopifnot(is.numeric(x) & is.logical(na.rm) & is.character(method))

So, we use the three inputs (separated by commas) because (1) it requires the least amount of typing (instead of three stopifnot()s), and (2) it is easier to read (instead of using &s).
Let’s see if it works! Here are a few unexpected, but reasonable inputs:

rescale(10:20, na.rm = "true", method = "min-max")

Error in `rescale()`:
! is.logical(na.rm) is not TRUE

rescale(10:20, na.rm = TRUE, method = 2)

Error in `rescale()`:
! is.character(method) is not TRUE



5.4.3 Checking Object Size
Another common input check is to verify that the object(s) being input are the correct size. For example, our rescale() function expects x to be a vector with at least two values. Why? When calculating the standard deviation of x, if the vector has only one value the standard deviation is an NA:

x &lt;- 5
sd(x)

[1] NA


To prevent this from happening, we can incorporate one additional check into our rescale() function. Specifically, we can check the length() of x and verify that it has more than 1 element:

rescale &lt;- function(x, na.rm = FALSE, method){

  # check if all inputs are correct data type
  # and x has at least two elements
  stopifnot(is.numeric(x), 
            is.logical(na.rm), 
            is.character(method), 
            length(x) &gt; 1
            )

  if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - min(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / (max(x, na.rm = TRUE) - min(x, na.rm = TRUE))
  } else if (method == "min-max" & na.rm == FALSE) {
    (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))
  } else if (method == "normalize" & na.rm == TRUE){
    (x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  } else{
    (x - mean(x)) / sd(x)
  }
}

Let’s see if it works!

x &lt;- 5
rescale(x, method = "min-max")

Error in `rescale()`:
! length(x) &gt; 1 is not TRUE








Check-inCheck In



We’ve incorporated a input check for the size of x, but not for the size of na.rm or method.

  stopifnot(is.numeric(x), 
            is.logical(na.rm), 
            is.character(method), 
            length(x) &gt; 1, 
            blahblahblah == 1, 
            blahblahblah == 1
            )


What length() should we expect na.rm to have? What length() should we expect method to have?
What additional input check should the function have?


Check if the numbers are all positive.
Check if the value specified for na.rm is either TRUE or FALSE.
Check if the value specified for method is either "min-max" or "normalize".
Check if the minimum or maximum are infinite.
